      textEn: [
        "A group of strapping young men.",
        "Behind them stretched a field of sorghum. They were as honest and plain as that sorghum.",
        "A hissing south wind stirred the sorghum leaves and ruffled their clothes.",
        "Their expressions were steady and calm. The waist drums fastened tight against their sides hung still, as if they had never sounded.",
        "But then: Look!—Once they started beating, they went wild, lost in abandon, drumming for their lives! A hundred-odd young men with drums slung across their backs danced madly before you like a hundred boulders hurled up again and again by a great earthquake. Like a cloudburst—the rapid drumbeats; like a whirlwind—the swirling tassels; like a swarm of frogs—the leaping feet; like sparks—the flashing eyes; like a tiger fight—the powerful bearing. On the Loess Plateau there burst forth a dance of such grandeur, such abandon, such blazing intensity—the Ansai waist drum!",
        "This waist drum instantly turned the freezing air scorching, the tranquil sunlight splashing, the drowsy world electrified.",
        "It made one think of: sunset blazing on the great banner, horses whinnying in the moaning wind!",
        "It made one think of: thunder rolling a thousand li, lightning flashing ten thousand li!",
        "It made one think of: obscurity yielding to clarity, clarity yielding to obscurity, and then the final, eternal clarity of total enlightenment!",
        "No room for shackles, no room for fetters, no room for stagnation. It was the raw force of breaking free, bursting through, smashing open!",
        "What an Ansai waist drum!",
        "The heavy booming of a hundred waist drums crashed against the cliffs lined with jujube trees on all sides, and the cliffs suddenly became rawhide drumheads—all you could hear was boom, boom, boom.",
        "The heavy booming of a hundred waist drums crashed against the hearts of the audience, who had shed all distractions, and their hearts too became rawhide drumheads—boom, boom, boom.",
        "A heroic lyricism of booming, a solemn meditation of booming, the booming of plow tips turning up waves of earth tangled with grass roots, the booming of birth pangs rising and subsiding...",
        "What an Ansai waist drum!",
        "The young men's arms, legs, entire bodies struck powerfully, struck swiftly, struck with great surges and plunges. It shook you, seared you, bore down on you. It made you feel the existence, vitality, and might of life more vividly than ever before. It made you marvel that those bodies wrapped in farmers' clothing, those bodies nourished on red bean pods and old pumpkin, could release such magnificent, overwhelming energy!",
        "O Loess Plateau, you raised these brimming, spirited young men; and only you could withstand such earth-shaking, soul-stirring combat!",
        "The watery south is fragile glass—there, you could never play such a waist drum.",
        "Besides the Loess Plateau, where else is there soil so thick, so very thick!",
        "What a Loess Plateau! What an Ansai waist drum!",
        "Every dance move brimmed with power. Every dance move whistled through the air. Every dance move was a swift interplay of light and shadow. Every dance move made one tremble in the intensity of artistic rapture, left one in speechless admiration.",
        "What an Ansai waist drum—one that thrills the mountains and rivers and ignites the imagination!",
        "The drumming grew ever more furious! Bodies became heavy yet whirling thoughts!",
        "The drumming grew ever more furious! In these thoughts, nothing remained hidden!",
        "The drumming grew ever more furious! Pain and joy, life and fantasy, escape and pursuit—all intertwined in the dance and drumbeats! Spinning! Converging! Surging! Radiating! Soaring! Sublimating! People became a vast blur; sound became a vast blur...",
        "When it stopped abruptly, the world was so strangely silent that one felt utterly unfamiliar with it.",
        "It was as if one had arrived on another planet.",
        "In one's ears lingered a distant cock's crow."
      ],
