      textEn: [
        "During the Taiyuan era of the Jin Dynasty, a fisherman of Wuling made his living catching fish. One day he followed a stream and lost track of how far he had gone. Suddenly he came upon a grove of peach trees in blossom, lining both banks for several hundred paces. There were no other trees among them; the fragrant grass was fresh and beautiful, and fallen petals lay scattered in profusion. The fisherman was greatly astonished and went on further, wishing to reach the end of the grove.",
        "Where the grove ended at the source of the stream, he found a mountain with a small opening that seemed to emit a faint light. He left his boat and entered through the opening. At first it was extremely narrow, barely wide enough for one person to pass. After walking several dozen more paces, it suddenly opened up into a bright, spacious land. The terrain was flat and broad, the houses neat and orderly, with fine fields, beautiful ponds, mulberry trees, and bamboo groves. Paths crisscrossed between the fields, and the crowing of roosters and barking of dogs could be heard from one homestead to the next. People came and went, tending their crops; the clothing of men and women was entirely like that of the outside world. The elderly and the children all appeared content and happy.",
        "Seeing the fisherman, the people were greatly startled and asked where he had come from. He answered all their questions in full. They then invited him to their home, set out wine, killed a chicken, and prepared a meal. When the other villagers heard of this visitor, they all came to inquire. They said their ancestors had fled the turmoil of the Qin Dynasty, bringing their families and fellow villagers to this isolated place, and had never gone out again, thus becoming cut off from the outside world. They asked what dynasty it was now; they did not even know there had been a Han Dynasty, let alone the Wei and Jin. The fisherman told them everything he knew, and they all sighed with wonder and regret. The other villagers each in turn invited him to their homes and served wine and food. After staying several days, he took his leave. The people told him: 'It is not worth mentioning this to outsiders.'",
        "After leaving, he found his boat and retraced his route, marking it at every point. When he reached the prefecture seat, he went to the prefect and reported everything. The prefect immediately sent men to follow him back, but they searched for the marks he had made and became lost, never finding the way again.\nLiu Ziji of Nanyang, a man of noble character, heard of it and happily planned to go, but he fell ill and died before he could. After that, no one inquired about it again."
      ],
