      textEn: [
        "In the Ming Dynasty there was a man of extraordinary ingenuity named Wang Shuyuan. He could carve palaces, vessels, human figures, and even birds, beasts, trees, and stones from a piece of wood no more than an inch in diameter, always following the natural grain to suggest forms, each with its own expression and posture. He once gave me a peach-pit boat, representing Su Dongpo's excursion to the Red Cliff.",
        "From bow to stern, the boat measured about eight-tenths of an inch, and its height was roughly two grains of millet. The tall, spacious midsection served as the cabin, covered with a bamboo-leaf awning. Small windows opened on both sides, four on the left and four on the right, eight in all. When the windows were opened, carved railings faced each other. When closed, on the right was inscribed 'The moon is small when the mountain is high; the rocks emerge when the water falls,' and on the left, 'A gentle breeze comes slowly; the water is still'—the characters filled in with azurite.",
        "At the bow sat three figures. The one in the middle, wearing a tall cap and with a full beard, was Su Dongpo. Foyin sat to the right, and Lu Zhi to the left. Su and Huang were examining a hand scroll together. Dongpo held the right end of the scroll in his right hand and rested his left hand on Lu Zhi's back. Lu Zhi held the left end of the scroll in his left hand and pointed at it with his right, as though speaking. Dongpo's right foot was visible, Lu Zhi's left foot was visible; each leaned slightly, and where their two knees met they were hidden in the folds of clothing beneath the scroll. Foyin bore an exact likeness to the Maitreya Buddha, bare-chested, head raised and gazing upward, his expression quite different from that of Su and Huang. His right knee lay flat, his right arm was bent to brace against the boat, his left knee was raised, and his left arm, draped with a string of prayer beads, leaned against it—the beads could be counted one by one.",
        "At the stern an oar lay across the boat. On either side of the oar stood a boatman. The one on the right had his hair in a bun and face turned upward, his left hand resting on a crossbar, his right hand grasping his right toes, as if whistling or calling. The one on the left held a palm-leaf fan in his right hand and rested his left hand on a stove, on which sat a kettle. His gaze was steady and his expression serene, as though listening to the sound of tea brewing.",
        "The bottom of the boat was somewhat flat, with an inscription carved there reading: 'On an autumn day of the renxu year of the Tianqi reign, carved by Wang Yi, courtesy name Shuyuan, of Yushan.' The characters were fine as a mosquito's legs, every stroke distinct, in black. There was also one seal in seal script reading 'Chuping Shanren,' in vermillion.",
        "In total, the boat contained five human figures; eight windows; one each of bamboo-leaf awning, oar, stove, kettle, hand scroll, and string of prayer beads; and the couplets, inscription, and seal text amounted to thirty-four characters altogether. Yet the whole thing measured less than an inch in length. It had been made from a carefully selected long, narrow peach pit. Goodness—what miraculous and marvelous skill!"
      ],
