      textEn: [
        "Guan Ju (The Ospreys)\n\n'Guan-guan' cry the ospreys, on the islet in the river.\nGentle and gracious is the maiden—a fine match for the gentleman.\nUneven water plants drift left and right.\nThe gentle maiden—waking and sleeping, he seeks her.\nSeeking but not finding her—waking and sleeping, he longs for her.\nEndlessly, endlessly—he tosses and turns.\nUneven water plants are gathered left and right.\nThe gentle maiden—with lute and zither he courts her.\nUneven water plants are sorted left and right.\nThe gentle maiden—with bells and drums he delights her.",
        "Jian Jia (The Reeds)\n\nThick grow the reeds, white dew has turned to frost.\nThe one I seek is somewhere across the water.\nGoing upstream to find her—the way is blocked and long.\nGoing downstream to find her—she seems amid the water.\nThick grow the reeds, white dew not yet dried.\nThe one I seek is at the water's edge.\nGoing upstream to find her—the way is blocked and steep.\nGoing downstream to find her—she seems upon a sandbar.\nThick grow the reeds, white dew not yet gone.\nThe one I seek is by the water's bank.\nGoing upstream to find her—the way is blocked and winding.\nGoing downstream to find her—she seems upon an islet."
      ],
