      textEn: [
        "The Officer at Shihao\nDu Fu\n\nAt dusk I sought lodging at Shihao Village; an officer came seizing people in the night.\nThe old man fled over the wall; the old woman went out to the door.\nHow furious the officer's shout! How bitter the woman's cry!\nI heard the woman step forward and speak: three sons sent to garrison at Ye City.\nOne son sent a letter home; two sons have recently died in battle.\nThe living barely scrape by; the dead are gone forever!\nNo man is left in the house—only a grandson still at the breast.\nBecause of the grandson, his mother has not left, but she has no decent skirt to go out in.\nThough this old woman's strength is fading, let me go back with the officer tonight.\nI can answer the urgent call to serve at Heyang—I can still prepare the morning meal.\nDeep into the night, voices ceased; I seemed to hear faint sobbing.\nAt dawn I set out again on my way—alone I bade the old man farewell.",
        "My Thatched Roof Is Ruined by the Autumn Wind\nDu Fu\n\nIn the eighth month, autumn gales howl with fury, rolling three layers of thatch from my roof.\nThe thatch flies across the river and scatters over the riverbank; some hangs caught in the treetops, some whirls down into pond hollows.\nThe village boys from the south bully me for being old and weak, brazenly snatching the thatch before my face like thieves.\nThey clutch the thatch and vanish into the bamboo; my lips are parched and my mouth dry—I cannot call them back. I come home leaning on my cane and sigh.\nSoon the wind dies and the clouds turn ink-black; the autumn sky stretches dim toward darkness.\nMy cotton quilt, old for years, is cold as iron; my restless child kicks it and tears the lining.\nAbove my bed, the roof leaks everywhere—no dry spot; the rain falls in threads, unceasing.\nSince the upheaval I have scarcely slept; how can I endure the long night, soaked through!\nOh, for a mansion of ten thousand rooms to shelter every poor scholar under heaven with joyful faces!\nFirm against wind and rain, steady as a mountain.\nAlas! When will such a building rise before my eyes? Even if my own hut is shattered and I freeze to death, I shall be content!",
        "The Old Charcoal Seller\nBai Juyi\n\nThe old charcoal seller cuts wood and burns charcoal deep in the southern hills.\nHis face is streaked with dust and soot, his temples grey, his ten fingers black.\nWhat does selling charcoal earn him? Clothes on his back, food in his mouth.\nPitiful—his clothes are thin, yet he worries that charcoal is cheap and wishes for colder weather.\nOvernight, a foot of snow falls outside the city; at dawn he drives his charcoal cart, grinding through the icy ruts.\nThe ox is spent, the man is hungry, the sun already high—he rests in the mud outside the south gate of the market.\nTwo riders come prancing up—who are they? A yellow-robed palace envoy and his white-shirted attendant.\nHolding an imperial decree aloud, they turn the cart around, curse the ox, and drag it northward.\nA full cartload of charcoal, over a thousand catties—the palace messengers drive it away; he cannot hold it back.\nHalf a bolt of red gauze and a length of silk, tied to the ox's head as the price of the charcoal."
      ],
